":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Wondrous’ or ‘enlightenment’.","2  ♀ ‘Fine jade’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guillaume II De Ferrières was born about 1118, in Ferrières en Gâtinais, Loiret, Centre-Val de Loire, France, his father, Guillaume Ier De Ferrières, was 44 and his mother, Elisabeth Isabelle De Chartres, was 17. He had at least 2 sons with Marguerite Inconnue. He died after 1180."},"et":{"about 1118–After 1180":"umbes 1118–pärast 1180","1118–1180":"1118–1180","1130–Female":"1130–Surnud","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1165–Male":"1165–Surnud","1075–1130":"1075–1130","1102–1155":"1102–1155","about 1160":"umbes 1160","before 1155":"enne 1155","1165":"1165","1